04371nam a22006135i 9780674041233DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212001mau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780674041233  a(DE-B1597)584874  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aR692 7aSCI0340002bisacsh04a610.69/52/08209731 aMore, Ellen S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRestoring the Balance :bWomen Physicians and the Profession of Medicine, 1850–1995 /cEllen S. More. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Restoring the Balance? -- t1 The Professionalism of Sarah Dolley, M.D. -- t2 Gendered Practices: Late Victorian Medicine in the Woman’s Sphere -- t3 Maternalist Medicine: Women Physicians in the Progressive Era -- t4 Redefining the Margins: Women Physicians and American Hospitals, 1900–1939 -- t5 Getting Organized: The Medical Women’s National Association and World War I -- t6 New Directions: The Eclipse of Maternalist Medicine -- t7 Resisting the “Feminine Mystique,” 1938–1968 -- t8 Medicine and the New Women’s Movement -- tConclusion: Reconciling Equality and Difference -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom about 1850, American women physicians won gradual acceptance from male colleagues and the general public, primarily as caregivers to women and children. By 1920, they represented approximately five percent of the profession. But within a decade, their niche in American medicine--women's medical schools and medical societies, dispensaries for women and children, women's hospitals, and settlement house clinics--had declined. The steady increase of women entering medical schools also halted, a trend not reversed until the 1960s. Yet, as women's traditional niche in the profession disappeared, a vanguard of women doctors slowly opened new paths to professional advancement and public health advocacy. Drawing on rich archival sources and her own extensive interviews with women physicians, Ellen More shows how the Victorian ideal of balance influenced the practice of healing for women doctors in America over the past 150 years. She argues that the history of women practitioners throughout the twentieth century fulfills the expectations constructed within the Victorian culture of professionalism. Restoring the Balance demonstrates that women doctors--collectively and individually--sought to balance the distinctive interests and culture of women against the claims of disinterestedness, scientific objectivity, and specialization of modern medical professionalism. That goal, More writes, reaffirmed by each generation, lies at the heart of her central question: what does it mean to be a woman physician?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067404123340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674041233423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674041233/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK